+### Question 4
+
+Let `j = 1 - i`.
+
+#### Mutual Exclusion
+
+**Yes**, the algorithm guarantees mutual exclusion.
+
+Informal proof:
+
+- A process can enter the critical section only by leaving the outer loop `while (flag[j] == 1)`.
+- Therefore, if process `i` enters the critical section while process `j` is trying to enter, then at the moment `i` exits that loop, either `flag[j] != 1`, or else `j` is not actually in the competing state represented by `flag[j] == 1`.
+- In particular, if one process changes its flag to `2`, then the other process's outer test `while (flag[1-i] == 1)` becomes false, so only the process whose opponent is **not** equal to `1` can proceed.
+- Thus both processes cannot simultaneously get past their outer `while (flag[1-i] == 1)` tests while the other still has flag value `1`.
+- So both cannot be in the critical section at the same time.
+
+#### Progress
+
+**Yes**, the algorithm guarantees progress.
+
+Informal proof:
+
+- If only one process wants to enter, then the other process has `flag == 0`, so the outer `while (flag[1-i] == 1)` is immediately false and the requesting process enters.
+- If both processes want to enter, then both may set `flag = 1`, but only the process whose `turn` value is no longer current will execute the `if (turn != i)` branch, set its own flag to `2`, and wait.
+- Once one process has set its flag to `2`, the other process sees that its opponent's flag is no longer `1`, so that other process can enter the critical section.
+- Therefore, when one or more processes want to enter and no process is in the critical section, the choice of who enters next is not postponed forever; one of them will enter.
+
+#### Bounded Waiting
+
+**No**, the algorithm does **not** guarantee bounded waiting.
+
+Counterexample:
+
+1. `P0` and `P1` both try to enter.
+2. `P0` executes `flag[0] = 1; turn = 0;`
+3. `P1` executes `flag[1] = 1; turn = 1;`
+4. `P0` now sees `flag[1] == 1` and `turn != 0`, so it executes:
+   `flag[0] = 2;`
+   then waits in `while (turn != 0 && flag[1] == 1)`.
+5. `P1` sees `flag[0] == 2`, so its outer loop condition `while (flag[0] == 1)` is false, and `P1` enters the critical section.
+6. `P1` exits and sets `flag[1] = 0`, but before `P0` can finish entering, `P1` immediately starts again and executes:
+   `flag[1] = 1; turn = 1;`
+7. `P0` is still stuck in `while (turn != 0 && flag[1] == 1)`, because now `turn == 1` and `flag[1] == 1` are both true again.
+8. `P1` again sees `flag[0] == 2`, so it enters the critical section again.
+
+By repeating steps 6-8 forever, `P1` can enter the critical section an unbounded number of times while `P0` continues waiting. Therefore bounded waiting is not satisfied.
